Can my old PC keep up with one of these high-speed modems?

Most PC's can keep up with any modem slower than 14.4kbps.  If you buy
a high-speed internal modem from PPI, it is based around a chip called
a UART, such as the NS16550AFN chip.  The UART provides a small buffer
for data, and improve data transfer speeds.  If you buy a PPI external
high-speed modem, check the serial controller in your PC to be sure it
includes a 16550 UART.  Of course, if you want to get really high data
transfer rates, you can get a special card like PPI's own PC-HSSP.

How can I find out what ROM and data pump are in my PPI modem?

Send your modem the ATI3 command.  It will return something like this:
PM288MT II V.FC[6R7] Version 3.15 (c) Practical Peripherals Inc. 1994.
Everything up to the first square bracket describes what PPI modem you
have.  Within the square brackets, the second character stands for the
manufacturer of the data pump - A for AT&T, R for Rockwell.  After the
brackets, the version number is the ROM that's in your modem.

I heard of a new ROM that fixes a bug in my PPI modem.  What do I do?

PPI usually revises the ROM two or three times during the time a model
of modem is available for sale.  If you buy one of the early ones, and
encounter bugs, call technical support and ask them for an updated ROM
chip.  They'll mail one out to you, and you can swap it in yourself.

